        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1492482595" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4510517471808033996">The first thing to say about <i>The Invention of Morel</i> is that the narrative flow is (mostly) excellent. Bioy creates a haunting, lonely, mysterious story, with creepy undertones, that compels you to read on. There are certain parts of the story I just couldn&apos;t buy as literal - nor could they be passed-off as surreal - so I think the book is best interpreted as something of an allegory; a contemplation of mortality and a kind of idealised love. <br/><br/>I didn&apos;t find the philosophical and metaphysical impli</span>
  <span id="freeText4510517471808033996" style="display:none">The first thing to say about <i>The Invention of Morel</i> is that the narrative flow is (mostly) excellent. Bioy creates a haunting, lonely, mysterious story, with creepy undertones, that compels you to read on. There are certain parts of the story I just couldn't buy as literal - nor could they be passed-off as surreal - so I think the book is best interpreted as something of an allegory; a contemplation of mortality and a kind of idealised love. <br /><br />I didn't find the philosophical and metaphysical implications of the eventual revelations to be entirely convincing. It has something of the arrested profundity of an episode of original series Star Trek, by which I mean that it's intriguing but not entirely coherent when you really think about it (the date of the novel's publishing is a mitigating factor here). <br /><br />But the story is well told, atmospheric, original, and at times quite poignant. A remarkable little novel that punches above its weight.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4510517471808033996" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

