<div id="review_4164637021" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4164637021" />
    <a title="Matthew Ted" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/57003346-matthew-ted"><img alt="Matthew Ted" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1578773686p2/57003346.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4164637021?book_show_action=true">Aug 09, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matthew Ted" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matthew Ted" href="/user/show/57003346-matthew-ted">Matthew Ted</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57003346-matthew-ted?shelf=lit-latin-american">lit-latin-american</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57003346-matthew-ted?shelf=lit-writ-spanish">lit-writ-spanish</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57003346-matthew-ted?shelf=20th-century">20th-century</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57003346-matthew-ted?shelf=read-2021">read-2021</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4164637021" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16734405844693735144">83rd book of 2021. Artist for this review is Argentinian painter Carlos Alonso. <br/><br/>4.5. I recommend this edition or any edition that includes the introduction by Jorge Luis Borges, an introduction that, for me, proceeded my knowledge of the actual novel. Borges famously called a novel by Casares &quot;perfect&quot;, and so I thought I had to read it, naturally, and it turned out to be this 1940 novella, <i>The Invention of Morel</i>. Borges says, &apos;I maintain that during no other era have there been novels with such</span>
  <span id="freeText16734405844693735144" style="display:none">83rd book of 2021. Artist for this review is Argentinian painter Carlos Alonso. <br><br>4.5. I recommend this edition or any edition that includes the introduction by Jorge Luis Borges, an introduction that, for me, proceeded my knowledge of the actual novel. Borges famously called a novel by Casares "perfect", and so I thought I had to read it, naturally, and it turned out to be this 1940 novella, <i>The Invention of Morel</i>. Borges says, 'I maintain that during no other era have there been novels with such admirable plots as <i>Turn of the Screw</i>, <i>The Trial</i>, <i>Voyage to the Center of the Earth</i>, and the one you are about to read, which was written in Buenos Aires by Adolfo Bioy Casares.' His judgement is partially dependent on the other novels listed; <i>Turn of the Screw</i> is an interesting novella but I wouldn't say "perfectly plotted"; <i>The Trial</i> is perhaps a better example but Kafka is hard to read for all he is brilliant ("I could never finish a novel by Kafka. But then neither could Kafka."—Martin Amis) and Casares is comparatively wonderful reading. The final line of his Introduction is this: 'I have discussed with the author the details of his plot. I have reread it. To classify it as perfect is neither an imprecision nor a hyperbole.' <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1628589909i/31754705._SX540_.jpg" width="400" height="291" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Naturally the novella is rather Borgesian. Certain elements also reminded me of <i>Lolita</i> (as this, as well as Nabokov's masterpiece, is, lurking within the narrative, a story about unrequited love). It is a story of shadows and the self. A man is on an island and appears to be paranoid about the police/authorities. On the island there are only three things: a museum, a chapel and a swimming pool. He is informed and then warned before going (fleeing?) to the island. '"There is only one possible place for a fugitive like you—it is an uninhabited island, but a human being cannot live there. Around 1924 a group of white men built a museum, a chapel, and a swimming pool on the island. The work was completed, and then abandoned."' More importantly he goes on to say, <br><blockquote>
  <i>"'it is known to be the focal point of a mysterious disease, a fatal disease that attacks the outside of the body and then works inward. The nails drop off the fingers and toes; the hair falls out. The skin and the corneas of the eyes die, and the body lives on for one week, or two at the most. The crew of a ship that had stopped there were skinless, hairless, without nails on their fingers or toes—all dead, of course—when they were found by the Japanese cruiser Namura. The horrified Japanese sank their ship."'</i>
</blockquote><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1489741982i/22244521._SY540_.jpg" width="400" height="603" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>—Illustration from book.<br><br>Another clear inspiration for the novella comes from Wells; Borges also says in his Introduction, 'the title alludes filially to another island inventor, Moreau': the island, the idea of "another" or the "other", that one is not alone. And where I think <i>The Island of Doctor Moreau</i> is a lesser work of Wells', that is, not as good as his other novels, it is clear to see it inspired this remarkable little book, which in the end we may call science-fiction in itself. Regarding praise for its plotting, it isn't misplaced. The novella moves with creeping intensity as a group of people arrive on the island and the protagonist attempts to hide from them but also study them. He does not know who they are or why they are here, or indeed, where they have come from. The quietness of the island, the empty corridors of the museum, the snakes and lizards that fester in the swimming pool, the mosquitos, the floods in the marshes, the mysterious mirrored room, the echoes, the voices, they all build slowly around our protagonist. It is a novel rife with loneliness and paranoia and the kind of horror that lingers under the surface, like snakes in a pool. </span>
  <a data-text-id="16734405844693735144" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


